column168: OUR OPERATOR OF A HEAVY LIFT MACHINE WAS TRANSFERRING AN ISO CONTAINER ONTO A FLAT TRAILER.  ON THE WAY TO THE TRAILER THE ISO CONTAINER DISLODGED AND DROPPED TO THE GROUND.  THE REAR UNLOADING VALVE RUPTURED. THE AREA WAS EVACUATED AND THE MACHINE OPERATOR WENT TO A MEDICAL CENTER FOR AN EVALUATION.  HE CHECKED OUT OKAY AND RETURNED TO WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS SUMMONED TO EXECUTE THE CLEAN UP.  THE MANUFACTURER OF THE MACHINE WAS CALLED IN TO INVESTIGATE THE REASON FOR THE FAILURE OF THE LOCKING DEVICE.  THEY DISCOVERED A SHORT CIRCUIT IN THE WIRING THAT CAUSED THE FAILURE.

EMPLOYEE WAS PLACING DRUMS ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR WHEN THE CAUGHT THE DRUM ON A CORNER OF A NEARBY PALLET.  THE PALLET BLOCKED THE APPROXIMATELY 4 INCHES FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  FIVE GALLONS WERE SPILLED ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR.

ON JUNE 13,1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1703 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, TANK CAR NUMBER ECUX 361055, LOADED WITH TOLUENE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A PIPE CONNECTION AT THE INDUCTION VALVE WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD. THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATE ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE. THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TO THE SITE. THE SHIPPER REPAIRED THE LEAK AT 1920 HOURS THAT SAME DAY. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: WHEN THIS PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED FOR OUTBOUND SERVICE AT THE FRGA FEDEX STATION.  IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST FOUND 3 OF 4 PLASTIC INNER BOTTLES WITH LOOSE CAPS.  THE SPILL WAS HANDLED PER FEDEX POLICY AND THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER, SINCE THIS WAS A LOCAL DELIVERY BACK TO THEIR COMPANY.

WHILE THIS PACKAGE WAS AT THE CHEEKTOWAGA STATION (BUFA), A HISSING SOUND WAS NOTICED COMING FROM INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  SINCE THIS BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED FOR OXYGEN, UN1072.  THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ONE OF THE TWO CYLINDERS OF OXYGEN LEAKING SLIGHTLY.  THIS WAS A BREATHING APPARATUS OXYGEN CYLINDER WITH A FLIP OPEN/CLOSE TOP, INSTEAD OF A NORMAL SCREW DOWN VALVE.  THE CLEAN UP SPECIALIST FLIPPED THE VALVE CLOSED AND CALLED DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION. WHEN HE CHECKED THE PRESSURE GAUGE WHILE CLOSING THE VALVE, HE FOUND IT TO BE ON ZERO.  THERE WAS NOTHING TO CLEAN UP AND THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE OUTER PACKAGING.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKED SORT WHEN THE DAMAGED/LEAKAGE OCCURED.  THE UNIT HAD APPARENTLY BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE CONTAINERS WERE PART OF A 30 PIECE SHIPMENT THAT ORIGINALLY TRANSITTED FROM HOUSTON, TEXAS INTO SANTIAGO  CHILE VIA MEMPHIS. WHILE TRANSITED THROUGH MEMPHIS 5-6 CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED BY FORKLIFT AND WERE BEING RETURNED TO THE ORIGIN SHIPPER IN HOUSTON. THE CONTAINERS WERE VERY ODOROUS AND AS A RESULT WE WERE FORCED TO SUSPEND OPERATIONS FOR AT LEAST SIX HOURS UNTIL CLEANUP AND REMOVAL COULD BE EFFECTED.  THE SHIPPER ELF ATOCHEM IN HOUSTON RESPONDED BRINGING WITH THEM THEIR SPILL CLEANUP  GROUP TO TAKE THE PUNCTURED DRUMS BACK TO THEIR LOCATION FOR CONTAINMENT AND DISPOSAL.  SEVEN PEOPLE IN THE OPERATION WERE AFFECTED BY THE FUMES FROM THIS MATERIAL.  AT LEAST ONE PERSON GOT THE MATERIAL ON THEIR HANDS CAUSING A STINGING/BURNING SENSATION.

column168: 6 CARTONS OF THE SHIPMENT WERE ON 1 WOODEN PALLET ON THE FLOOR OF THE TLR. DOCKMAN LOADING PIPE DOWN THE SIDE OF TLR. CRUSHED 1 CARTON CAUSING LIQUID TO ESCAPE FROM 1 OF THE 2 JUGS WITHIN THE CARTON. CARTON WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND ISOLATED APPROX 200 FEET FROM LOADING AREA. ABSORBANT MATERIAL PLACED AROUND CARTON AND AT POINT OF SPILL. ALL AFFECTED PRODUCT, ABSORBANT MATERIAL, AND 1 PAIR OF NEOPRENE GLOVES HAVE BEEN PLACED IN A 25 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK PENDING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER. CHEM TREC WAS CONTACTED AND MSDS OBTAINED. ALL ITEMS BEING HELD AT OUR HOUSTON FACILITY.
SPILL WAS CAUSED BY LOOSE CAP ON 1 GAL BOTTLE OF CORROSIVE LIQUID BALANCE OF LIQUID CONTAINED IN HAZ MAT CONTAINER.

column168: THE DSR OPENED THE TRAILER AND NOTICED A ODOR, AFTER A FEW MINUTES AFTER ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO AIR OUT HE BEGAN TO LOOK FOR THE NATURE OF THE ODOR HE LOCATED A TOTE AND DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. AFTER CONTACTING NALCO, WE PLACED THE TOTE IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA AND BEGAN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WITH SOME CLAY ABSORBANT. NALCO INDUSTRIES TOLD US TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT FOR PICK AND DISPOSAL BY GARNER ENVIR.

CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADER WAS FILLING TOTES. ONE OF THE TOTES HAD A CRACKED VALVE ON THE BOTTOM. DRIVER SHUT DOWN VALVE ON CARGO TANK AND UNLOADER AND CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL CONTAINED PRODUCT, NEUTRAILED AND CLEANED UP AREA.

DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING CARGO TANK INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK. HE WAS ABOUT 1/2 EMPTY WHEN THE STORAGE TANK STARTED TO OVERFLOW. IT WAS CONTAINED IN THE DIKED CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AROUND THE STORAGE TANK. THE CONSIGNEE TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.

column168: DRIVER WAS TOLD TO START PUMPING LOAD OFF AND ALL VALVES WERE OPEN. HE STARTED AND THE UNLOADING HOSE RUPTURED RIGHT AWAY. THE CONSIGNEE HAD FAILED TO OPEN THE VALVE ON THE UNLOADING LINE. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF IPA WAS RELEASED ONTO THE CONCRETE UNLOADING PAD AND EVAPORATED.

WHILE DRUMMING OFF PRODUCT, THE PUMP STARTED TO LABOR AND THE DRIVER STARTED OPENING HIS BYPASS BUT THE HOSE END BURST BEFORE HE COULD COMPLETELY OPEN IT. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF RESIN SPRAYED OUT. THE CONSIGNEE AND DRIVER PUT OIL DRY ON THE SPILL AND SHOVELED UP FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: ILLINOIS CENTRAL TRAIN CREW ON TRAIN GENS 13 SOUTHBOUND OUT OF GEISMAR YARD OBSERVED VAPORS COMING FROM THE TOPCENTER OF TANK CAR GATX 61098. ALL APPROPRIATE LOCAL AND STATE AGENCIES WERE CALLED. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED FOR SHIPPER CONTACT. BASF TEAM RESPONDED TO SCENE AND FOUND THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS THE BLIND FLANGE ON THE EDUCATION TUBE. THEY FOUND THAT ALL FOUR (4) BOLTS SECURING THE BLIND FLANGE WERE LOOSE. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH OF PLAY ON EACH BOLT. BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK SECURED. CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: CONWAY EMPLOYEE ENTERED TRAILER WITH FORKLIFT TO REMOVE SHIPMENT THAT WAS PALLETIZED ON A 4' WIDE AND 2' LONG PALLET. HE DROVE THE FORKLIFT BLADES PAST THE LENGTH OF THE PALLET RUPTURING THE DRUM AHEAD OF THE PALLET. THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE DRUMS.

SHIPMENT WAS OFFLOADED FROM A TRUCK ON THE 16TH OF JUNE 1999. IT WAS RECEIVED IN GOOD ORDER & CONDITION AND STORED IN THE DGR AREA FOR LOCAL DELIVERY. ON JUNE 19, A WARE HOUSEMAN NOTICED LEAKING IN THE SURROUNDING AREA AND INFORMED HIS SUPERIOR. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT  & THE FAA WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPT. THE RESPONSE TEAM EVACUATED THE BUILDING WHILE PATCHING THE DRUM. FIRE CHIEF INFORMED US TO DELIVER THE DRUM WITH THE SKID ATTACHED. THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE GOODS WERE DELIVERED OUT OF OUR WAREHOUSE ON THE 23RD JUNE.

CARGO TANK OVERFILL ALARM MALFUNCTIONED DURING THE LOADING OPERATION. OVERFILL ALARM SYSTEM HAS BEEN REPAIRED. DRIVER/OPERATOR COUNSELED TO BE MORE ATTENTIVE TO OPERATING RESPONSIBILITIES. CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN BIOREMEDIATED ON SITE.

TERMINAL PERSONNEL FOUND SPILLED PRODUCT IN TRAILER.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  MSDS CAME WITH FREIGHT.  APPEARS DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY NAIL IN TRAILER FLOOR.  TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM OVERPACKED DAMAGED DRUM WITH CLEANUP MATERIALS.  DRUM IS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.  REST OF SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO CONSIGNEE.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A DAMAGED BAG. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED. APPEARS BAG WAS PUNCTURED DURING LOADING.  TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM SWEPT UP FREE PRODUCT AND PLACED IT INTO A HAZMAT BAG WITH CLEANUP MATERIALS.  BAG WAS PLACED INTO A HAZMAT BAG AND TAPED TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE.  BAG IS BEING FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE WITH REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED LEAKING DRUM. APPARENTLY THE BUNG HAD LOOSENED RELEASING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  AN MSDS HAD ACCOMPANIED SHIPMENT.  FREE PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED.  CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND DRUM WAS FORWARDED WITH REST OF SHIPMENT TO CONSIGNEE.

WHILE MOVING A WRANGLER BAG CONTAINING SOLID WASTE MATERIAL, FIVE GALLONS OF LIQUID MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE BAG ONTO THE  WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE WASTE WAS ABSORBED AND RECOVERED FROM THE FLOOR.  ALL THE MATERIAL FROM THE SPILL AND THE ORIGINAL BAG WAS PLACED INTO A NEW BAG FOR TRANSPORT.  THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIFTY POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 300 CANAL ST, LAWRENCE, MA FOR EVENTUAL TRANSFER TO A TREATMENT/DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE WAREHOUSEMAN WAS BRIEFED TO CHECK  FOR LOOSE LIQUIDS IN CONTAINERS PRIOR TO MOVING WASTE BAGS.

column168: A DRIVER LOADING A WASTE DRUM ONTO HIS TRUCK PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ON A PROTRUSION, CAUSING TWO GALLONS OF WASTE TO LEAK INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER OVER PACKED THE DRUM AND ABSORBED AND RECOVERED THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER OVER PACK.  THIS SPILL GENERATED TWENTY POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET, DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO WATCH FOR PROTRUSIONS THAT MAY PUNCTURE WASTE DRUMS WHEN LOADING THEM ONTO HIS TRUCK.

THE GENERATOR PACKAGED FILTER CAKE WASTE INTO A CUBIC YARD BOX FOR TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL.  THE WASTE WAS SUPPOSED TO BE 100% SOLID.  SOMETIME AFTER THE WASTE WAS PACKAGED CONDENSATE/LIQUID PERMEATED THROUGH THE LINER OF THE BOX.  THE LIQUID MADE CONTACT WITH THE BOX CAUSING THE CONTAINER FAILURE.

PTL DRIVER STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP TO SHOWER.  WHEN HE CAME OUT OF THE TRUCK STOP HE DISCOVERED THAT PRODUCT.  HAD LEAKED OUT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND.  DRIVER CONTACTED PASCHALL TRUCK LINES AND PASCHALL NOTIFIED EMI WHO SENT A SUBCONTRACTOR OUT OF MEMPHIS TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW AND THE INSURANCE ADJUSTER THAT AIR BAGS HAD BEEN USED TO BLOCK AND BRACED THE LOAD FROM MOVEMENT.  THE AIR BAG IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER HAD NOT BEEN FULLY INFLATED THEREFORE THREE OF THE FIVE GALLON PAILS HAD SLID FROM THE PALLET AND PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM AROUND THE SEALS ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SPILL  WAS CLEANED UP AND THE LOAD WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER TO BE RE-WORKED AND REBRACE.  THEN THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO DESTINATION POINT.

column168: DRIVER WANTED TO CHECK LEAKING VALVE.  PULLED CAP OFF TO CHECK BUT INTERNAL VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPENED DUE TO SLUDGE IN ELBOW.  EXTERNAL TEMPERATURE WAS OVER 90 F.   DRIVER DID NOT HOOK UP TRACTOR TO VAC AND THE PRESSURE BUILT UP IN TANK ALONG WITH THE SLIGHTLY OPENED INTERNAL VLAVE WHICH RESULTED IN A DISCHARGED OF MATERIAL (APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS).  THE AREA WAS DIKED OFF AND MATERIAL ABSORBED UP WITH PADS.  CAP WAS REPLACED O THE TANKER TO STOP FLOW. SOLID CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL.  DIRT AND GRAVEL FROM THE PARKING LOT WAS EXCAVATED TO FOUR (4) AND AFTER EXCAVATION. PERSONNEL WERE CHECKED OUT BY HSO AND FIRST AID WAS ISSUED.  SHOWERE WERE TAKEN BY CONTAMINATED PERSONNEL.  VALVES WILL BE INSPECTED BY BULK CARRIERS (TANK INSPECTION FACILITY).  ALL PERSONNEL AGAIN WILL BE ADDRESSED IN THE NEXT DRIVER MEETING ABOUT LEAKING VALVES, PPE LEVELS AND WEATHER CONDITIONS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: APPROXIMATELY 20 CUBIC YARDS OF WASTE MATERIAL AND RESPONSE DEBRIS WAS GENERATED.  APPROXIMATELY 24,500 GALLONS OF TREATED WASTE WAS CREATED AS A RESULT OF THE TREATMENT METHOD OF 20-30% LIME AND A 4-6 TIMES DILUTION USED BY THE RESPONDING COMPANY.  APPROX 2,100 GALLONS OF NON TREATED WASTE WAS RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR AS WAS ALL OF THE AFOREMENTIONED WASTE.  THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT WAS TAKEN TO THE GENERATOR, REMTECH GROUP, 550 INDUSTRIAL DRIVE, LEWISBERRY, PA 17339.  1 HOUR AND 15 MINUTES FROM THE GENERATOR REMTECH GROUP. LEWISBERRY, PA, THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE TRAILER BURST.  THE DRIVER SAW A RED CLOUD COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND QUICKLY BROUGHT THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO A STOP.  30 GALLONS OF WASTE ACID SPILLED TO THE PAVEMENT ON ROUTE 11 AND 15 AS A RESULT OF LIQUIDS SPLASHING OUT OF THE RUPTURE DISK APPERTURE.   THE WASTE WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVEMENT ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE COMPANY.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO STOP TRAFFIC, PLACE THE EMERGENCY EQUIPMENT OUT, AS WELL AS NOTIFY THE GENRATOR AND THE SITE OF THE INCIDENT.  FURTHER NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED.  AGENCIES RESPONDED AS WELL AS THE CONTRACT RESPONSE SERVICE.  THE WASTE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR AND THE SITE OF THE INCIDENT. FURTHER NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED. AGENGIES RESPONDED AS WELL AS THE CONTRACT RESPONSE SERVICE.  THE WASTE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR.  THE TRANSPORTER WAS NOT INFORMED THAT THE WASTE WOULD REACT IF STIRRED.  THE WASTE WAS A COMPOSITE OF A NUMBER OF DRUMS.  IT WOULD HAVE BEEN VERY HARD FOR THE DRIVER TO TELL THAT THE WASTE ACID WAS REACTING BECAUSE THE LIQUID WASTE WOULD ROLL AND BE AGITATED AS IT WAS PUMPED FROM DRUMS.  THE ROAD WAS CLOSED FOR ABOUT 30 HOURS, 1000 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THE AREA.  6 PEOPLE WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED WITH MINOR BURNS TO THE ARM AND NASAL PASSAGES. NO VEHICLES WERE REPORTEDLY DAMAGED EXCEPT FOR THE TANKER.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT WASTE WHICH DID NOT MATCH THE WASTE PROFILE WAS LOADED ON TO THE TRAILER BY REMTECH GROUP EMPLOYEES.

column168: ON JUNE 17, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1155 HOURS, A HIGHWAY VAN TRAILER, LOADED WITH A LESS THAN TRUCK LOAD OF ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHILE THE TRAILER WAS BEING OFF LOADED FROM INTER MODAL RAIL SERVICE AT KCS' INTER MODAL FACILITY, OPERATED BY IN-TERMINAL LOCATED AT DALLAS, TEXAS.  AFTER THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, THE AREA WAS SECURED AND APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE CONDUCTED.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS NOTIFIED.  BOOTS & COOTS SPECIAL SERVICES (BCSS), EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, OUT OF DALLAS, TEXAS WAS MOBILIZED TO THE SITE FOR ASSESSMENT, CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP.  THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY THE IMPROPER LOADING AND SECUREMENT OF LADING WITHIN THIS TRAILER, WHERE A PALLET OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID JUGS WAS STACKED AND TOP OF A PALLET OF SAME, RESULTING IN CRUSHED AND RUPTURED CONTAINERS. ALL RUPTURED CONTAINERS WERE OVER-PACKED AND ALL RELEASED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP BY BCSS.

AFTER BEGINNING TO UNLOAD, THE DRIVER SHUTDOWN THE UNLOAD PROCEDURE AND WENT INSIDE THE CONSIGNEE'S BUILDING.  WHILE INSIDE HE WAS OVERCOME BY VAPORS/GASES THAT RESULTED IN HIS DEATH. A SECOND MAN, AN EMPLOYEE OF THE CONSIGNEE WAS ALSO EXPOSED TO THE VAPOR/ GAS AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL. column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: TRAILER ARRIVED WITH EVIDENCE OF CLEAR SUBSTANCE THAT HAD LEAKED AND DRIED ON THE RIGHT REAR EXTERIOR.  TTAILER TAKEN TO SAFE HAVEN AND INSPECTION REVEAKED DRUM PUNCTURED @ LOWERING ROLLING HOOP BY WOOD PALLET BOLTS OF ADJACENNT LDING AGAINST DRUM.  LEAK HAD STOPPED AND SPILLED PRODUCT DRIED.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR REMEDIATED SPILLED PRODUCT AND OVER PACKED DAMAGED DRUM.

OUTBOUND DRIVER NOTICED SMALL DRIED PRODUCT SPILL AT REAR DOOR AND TRAILER HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY SHIPPER CONTRACTOR WHOM FOUND 3 DRUMS WITH LOOSE BUNGS.  PALLET THAT DRUMS WRER LOADED UPON DISMANTLED FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL.  CONTRACTOR ADJUSTED LOAD AND TRAILER RELEASED TO CONSIGNEE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: PRODUCT LEAKING FROM DOME AREA DURING YARD SWITCH MOVEMENT AND CAR ISOLATED.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR FOUND MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE AND GASKET DISENGAGED; LIQUID EDUCTION LINE SLEEVE LOOSE AND VALVE CRACKED.  LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE AND MANWAY GASKET REPLACED; AFTERWARDS MANWAY COVER BOLTS TIGHTNED.  SPILLED PRODUCT THAT DIDN'T EVAPORATE WAS WIPED CLEANED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE BEING DERAMPED. DRIVER NOTICED TRAILER LEAKING SIBSTANCE OUT REAR DOORS AND TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT PIT.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR FOUND ONE 5 GALLON PAIL PUNCTURED AT THE BOTTOM BY NAIL PROTRUSION FROM A SMALL PALLET USED FOR BRACING.  CONTRACTOR CLEANED PRODUCT AND DISPOSED OF DAMAGED PAIL.

BNSF YARD SWITCH CREW ODOR EMANATING FROM A CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND MANWAY COVER GASKET MISSING.  RUBBER MANWAY COVER GASKET INSTALLED, MANWAY COVER AND ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE TOOL TIGHTNED.  CAR RELEASED  TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER TO BENOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

UPON ARRIVAL, TRAILER WAS REPORTED LEAKING AND TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT PIT.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR FOUND DRUM AT REAR OF TRAILER WITH SMALL PUNCTURE ON BOTTOM OF DRUM DUE TO BEING PLACED ATOP AN UNKNOWN OBJECT DURING LOADING.  SPILLED PRODUCT ON RAILCAR AND IN TRAILER AND  SCRAPPED CLEANED AND REMOVED.  DRUM OVERPACKED AND REPLACED IN CLEANED TRAILER.

TRAILER ARRIVED DRIPPING LIQUID ONTO RAILCAR.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR INVESTIGATED AND FOUND CRACK AT BOTTOM INCH OF ONE PLASTIC BUCKET CAUSED BY LOAD SHIFTED PALLET THAT RESTED AGAINST BUCKET.  LEAKING BUCKET OVERPACKED ALONG WITH TWO OTHER DAMAGED BUCKETS.  CONTRACTOR REMEDIATED ALL SPILLED PRODUCT THAT HAD NOW DRIED AND ADJUSTED TRAILER LOAD.

TRAIN STOPPED IN SIDING AFTER REPORTS OF ODOR EMANATING FROM A CAR. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND ASBESTOS MANWAY COVER GASKET DETERIORATED AND REPLACED IT WITH A RUBBER MANWAY GASKET, AS SIMILAR GASKET NOT READILY AVAILABLE RESPONDERS.  SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.
DRIVER ACCIDENTLY OVERFILLED TANK.  DRIVER TRAINING REINFORCED.

DRIVER WAS LOADING THRU THE BOTTOM OF TRAILER.  4 BOLT FLANGE FITTING BLEW OFF OF HOSE CAUSE A SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Ripped or Torn
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRACTOR TRAILER ROLL OVER CAUSED THE INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS (IBC), FILLED WITH A PLASTER AND ASBESTOS MATERIAL, TO RUPTURE FROM THE FORCE OF THE TRAILER AND LOAD COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE GROUND. WHEN DISCOVERED, AN ASBESTOS ABATEMENT CONTRACTOR WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  THE BROKEN PACKAGINGS WERE CONTAINED AND TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER, THEN BROUGHT TO A SECURE SITE.  AT THE SECURE SITE ALL PACKAGINGS WERE INSPECTED FOR INTEGRITY AND MARKING/LABELING.  ANY PACKAGINGS THAT DID NOT MEET THE PACKAGING STANDARDS WERE REPACKAGED BEFORE TRANSPORTING.  NO PACKAGING IMPROVEMENTS ARE RECOMMENDED AT THIS TIME.  THE PACKAGINGS WITHSTOOD THE INCIDENT VERY WELL, ONLY TWO OF FORTY PACKAGES FAILED AND NEEDED TO BE REPACKAGED.

column168: TRUCK STOPPED AT ITS FIRST OF THREE DELIVERY DESTINATIONS.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED WHERE TO UNLOAD THE 300 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, AND WHEN HE INTRODUCED PRODUCT INTO THE HOSE SPOOL SYSTEM, PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE VALVE ON THE HOSE SPOOL.  THE VALVE HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED IN THE FULL CLOSED POSITION, AND THE DRIVER HAD FAILED TO CHECK PRIOR TO OPENING TRAILER INTERNAL VALVE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH SPILL PADS AND BOOMS BY PLANT PERSONNEL.  A PROFESSIONAL SPILL CLEANUP CONTRACT FIRM WAS CALLED IN BY THE CUSTOMER- CITGO.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY WAS FERGUSON HARBOUR OF JACKSON, MS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND O WATERWAY WAS AFFECTED BY THIS RELEASE.

TRUCKED STOPPED ABRUPTLY ON THE ROAD JUST OUTSIDE THE GATE TO THE HERCULES, INC PLANT.  DRIVER WENT INTO GUARD HOUSE TO CHECK IN. WHEN HE CAME BACK, HE NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE DOME AREA THE PLANT RESPONSE GROUP WAS CALLED OUT AND CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL MATERIAL.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS LATER DETERMINED TO BE A DEFECTIVE GASKET IN THE DOME CLOSURE ASSEMBLY.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED BY PUMP, NO FURTHER LEAKAGE OCCURRED, THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAYS. TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO CARRIERS LIMERICK PENNSYLVANIA TERMINAL FOR FURTHER EXAMINATION AND REPAIRS.

column168: THIS LETTER IS TO ADVISE ALL CONCERNED PARTIES THAT IN JUNE 9, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 AM CENTRAL TIME, A C-RENTAL TRUCK MAKING A DELIVERY OF CHEMICAL TO DISTRIBUTORS IN MONROE,DELHI, AND LAKE POVIDENCE HAD THE 48 FOOT TRIALER CATCH FIRE. AT THIS TIME THE REASON FOR THE FIRE HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED, BUT FROM EVIDENCE THUS FAR IT APPEARD THAT THE BEARINGS ON LEFT SIDE OF THE AXLE FROZE CAUSING THE UNIT TO OVERHEAT AND BECOME ENFLAMED. BY THE TIME IT WAS NOTICED, ANY ALL EFFORTS TO EXTINGUISH THE FLAMES FAILED AND THE DRIVER HAD TO DISCONNECT THE TRAILER AND NOTIFY ADDITIONAL HELP. THIS LOAD HAD SEVERAL AGRICULTURAL CHEMCIALS THAT CONSISTED OF SOME HAZARDOUS PRODUCT AS WELL AS THE MAJORITY BEING NON- HAZARDOUS. WHEN THE INCIDENTS HAPPENED, THE DRIVER CONTACTED 911 FOR ASSISTANCE. HE COMMUNICATED THE PROBLEM TO COMPANY OFFICIALS AS WELL. AT THIS TIME, IMMEDIATE RESPONSE FROM THE CLOSESTFIRE DEPARTMENT (EUDORA VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT), C-RENTAL MANAGEMENT, AND NUMEROUS STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES RESPONDED FOE A GROUP EFFORT TO ASSURE IMMEDIATE ATTENTION TO THE PROBLEM. UPON ARRIVAL, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TRIED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT WITH WATER. BUT, DUE TO THE NUTURE OF THE FIRE, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO CEASE THAT APPROACH. AT THIS TIME, THE FIRE WAS ALLOWED TO BURN FREELY BASED ON THE DECISION OF THE WEATHER AND WIND CONDITIONS AS WELL AS THE LOCATION THAT SHOWED VERY MINIMAL THREAT TO THE AREA. THETRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO BURN FOR ABOUT (5) HOURS. BUT DUE TO THE CHANGING WINDS AND DECLINE IN THE BURNING OF THE TRIALER, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO SMOTER THE FIRE OUT WITH SAND. THIS PROCESS TOOK APPROZIMATELY 30 MINUTES. BY THIS TIME, THE IT CORPORATION OUT OF HOUSTON, TEXAS HAD RESPONDED FOR THE COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION. DESTROYED, BUT AT THIS TIME NO REPORTS OF INJURY OR ENVIRONMENTAL HAZARDS HAVE BEEN REPORTED.

ON ARRIVAL AT CHICAGO'S TERMINAL, A PALLET CONTAINING PAILS OF RESIN SOLUTION WAS FOUND TO BE CRUSHED.  THERE WAS LEAKAGE FROM THE PAIL. THE MATERIAL DRIED AND HARDEN.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CREDIT AND INSPECTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: A DRUM OF CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS FOUND TO BE LOOKING SLIGHTLY FROM A CRACK THAT DEVELOPED DURING TRANSIT.  IT WAS HELD, TURNED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND OVERPACKED.  DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CREDIT AND INSPECTION.
A DRUM OF CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS DAMAGED LOADING AT THE TERMINAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS TURNED TO PREVENT LEAKAGE AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS DISPOSED OF BY A WASTE DISPOSAL COMPANY.

TRAILER WAS DROPPED OFF AT THE TERMINAL OVER THE WEEKEND.  UPON ARRIVAL EARLY MONDAY MORNING, A LEAK WAS NOTICED IN THE TRAILER. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CREW RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THE LEAK STEMMED FROM THE PLASTIC TOTE RUBBING ON THE PALLET CAUSING A SMALL HOLE WHICH ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO LEAK.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: DRIVER DELIVERING IN INDUSTRIAL PARK; HAD TOTE TANK PULLED TO REAR OF TRAILER FOR NEXT STOP AS CONSIGNEE HAD NO DOCK TO GET TOTE FROM NOSE OF TRAILER.  AS HE WAS LEAVING CUSTOMERS PLACE, A PICK-UP TRUCK RAN A STOP SIGN AND CAUSE DRIVER TO LOCK UP ON THE BRAKES.  IT WAS EITHER LOCK THE BRAKES UP OR HIT THE PICK UP TRUCK BROADSIDE AND CAUSE SERIOUS DAMAGE AND POSSIBLE INJURY TO OTHER DRIVER.  THE TANK FLIPPED OVER END FOR END AND RUPTURED THE RELIEF VALVE.

PAIL WAS NOT PROTECTED PROPERLY IN TRAILER AND NOT VISIBLE TO D/S/R WHEN UNLOADING TRAILER.  FORKLIFT BLADE STRUCK PAIL AND DENTED SIDE IN.  WHEN PAIL WAS SEEN BY D/S/R PAIL WAS NOT LEAKING AND WAS PUT IN OS&D BAY.  LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY OPENING CREW NEXT MORNING.  THERE WAS AN ORAL DISCUSSION AND VERBAL REPRIMAND WITH ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED.  THEY HAVE BEEN RETRAINED IN THE HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AS WELL.
GAUGE WAS OFF
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: PAIL HIT BY OTHER FREIGHT ISOLATED.  SHIPPER AUTHORIZED DISPOSITION.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: PAIL NOTICED DAMAGED ON ARRIVAL AT TERMINAL MOVED IT TO AN ISOLATED AREA.  CONTACTED SHIPPER FOR INSTRUCTIONS.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: APPARENTLY THE DRAIN SPOUT WAS HIT DURING TRANSPORTATION WHICH CRACKED THE LATCH ON THE TOTE BIN AND OPENED THE VALVE.  CAL-TRANS RESPONDED TO ASSES THE SITUATION.  THE BUTTE COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED FOR ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND PRODUCT IDENTIFICATION.  AC INDUSTRIAL SERVICES CORP. OF CHICAGO RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO THE FREE LIQUID ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE AND INSIDE OF THE TRAILER.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT INVOLVED, THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED QUICKLY ONCE CONTACT WITH THE AIR OCCURRED.  ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED BY AC INDUSTRIAL SERVICES CORP. TO CROSBY & OVERTON FOR DISPOSAL.  ADDITIONAL RESPONSE PLANS DO NOT EXIST AT THIS TIME. THERE WERE NOT INJURIES OR EXPOSURE REPORTED.

UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION SOME PRODUCT WAS NOTICED ON TOP AND SIDE OF CONTAINER.  THE FACILITY CLEAN THE PRODUCT FROM THE DRUM AND FINISHED UNLOADING.  THE BUNG ON THE DRUM WAS LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE PACKAGE.

DRIVER WAS DELIVERIGN TO TRACTOR SUPPLY.  HE OPENED HIS TRAILER DOOR HE NOTICED 1-DRUM HAD SLID AND WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE.  HE SET THE DRUM BACK UP AND NOTICED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM A LOOSE CAP ON THE DRUM.  DRIVER SAID THAT " A GALLON MAY HAVE SPILLED OUT".  DRIVER PUT OIL DRY TO KEEP IT FROM SPREADING.  HE BOUGHT TRAILER BACK TO THE TERMINAL.  WE MOVED FREIGHT OFF THAT TRAILER TO ANOTHER AND CLEANED UP SPILL.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED ON THE BOX. EXAMINATION OF THEINNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE CONTAINER(S) HAD LOOSE CAP(S) AND LEAKED. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. THE CAP(S) WERE SECURED. THE CARTON WAS WET BUTOTHERWISE UNDAMAGED. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: UPON TRANSPORTATION OF RMW TO OUR TRANSFER FACILITY.  RMW IS BROUGHT INTO OUR STORAGE FACILITY AWAITING TRANSFER TO A LONG HAUL VEHICLE AT 6:30AM I NOTICED A RELEASE ON THE TRANSFER FACILITY FLOOR. I IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE SPILL, THEN CLEANED & DISINFECTED AREA WITH A BLEACH SOLUTION.  I THEN PLACED ABSORBENT PADS OVER THE SPILL TO SOAK UP ALL LIQUID.  AT THAT TIME I REPACKAGED ALL MATERIAL INTO 3-4-5- BOXES.  FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT THE HOSPITAL IS TO BE NOTIFIED ABOUT PROPER PACKAGING PROCEDURES.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: THREE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, BUT IT WAS DECIDED THAT SINCE THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND NOT MOVING, ADDITIONAL WORK SHOULD WAIT UNTIL IT COULD BE SAFELY DONE IN DAYLIGHT HOURS.

DIXIE CHEMICALHAD OFF LOADED THE TANK CAR USING NITRGEN AND HAD FAILED TO RELIEVE THE EXCESS PRESSURE.  H.L. BART VENTED THE EXCESSIVE PRESSURE AND REPOSITIONED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE GASKET. THE LEAKAGE STOPPED AND CAR WAS FORWARDED TO BILLED DESTINATION.
THAE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  THE RUPTURED DISC HAD BEEN BLOWN, IT WAS REPLACED WITH LIKE KIND SECURED..THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT MIDNIGHT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING VAPOR IN ALFALA YARD.  THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  A PUMPER TRUCK RESPONDED AS A SAFETY PRECAUTION, TO HELP KNOCK DOWN ANY VAPORS THAT MIGHT BE ADJACENT NEIGHBORHOOD.

THIS WAS AN INTERMODAL SHIPMENT THAT ORIGINATED IN JAPAN.  WE PICKED UP THE CONTAINER AT THE CSX RAILROAD IN BEDFORD PARK, IL AND DELIVERED TO GREEN BAY, WI.  THE CONTAINER WAS BACKED INTO THE DOCK FOR UNLOADING.  DURING THE UNLOADING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT DURING TRANSPORTATION PALLETS HAD SHIFTED AND RUBBED AGAINST 2 BAGS CAUSING SOME SPILLAGE OF MATERIAL.
column172: Plastic, coated with liner, for solids

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: LOCAL HAMTRAMCK FIRE DEPT. REPORTED TO GTW AND INDUSTRY THAT TANK CAR ON INDUSTRIAL SIDING WAS LEAKING GASOLINE.  FIRE DEPARTMENT MARSHALL STOPPED OPERATION ON GTW ADJACENT MAIN LINE TRACKAGE UNTIL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AWAY TO VACUM SPILLAGE.  SOURCE OF LEAK EMITTED FROM 1/2" SAMPLE PORT PERMANENTLY ATTACHED TO PIPING INSTALLED BY INDUSTRY TO TANK CAR BOTTOM UNLOADING VALVE FITTING. THE 1/2" SAMPLE PORT VALVE WAS OPENED BY BEING STRUCK BY BOTTOM UNLOADING VALVE CAP ATTACHED TO TANK CAR WITH CHAIN AND SWINGING FREELY BY WIND FORCES.  ALSO, HAND TIGHTENED BOTTOM UNLOADING VALVE DID NOT SEAT PROPERLY ALLOWING PRODUCT TO DRAIN OUT SAMPLING PORT. INDUSTRY MUST DEVELOP FAIL-SAFE UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER,  A FORKLIFT DRIVER PUNCTURED THE 55 GALLON DRUM CAUSING APPROX 1 OUNCE TO RELEASE.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PUT INTO A 85 GALLON OVERPACK ALONG WIT THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUM. CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS, INC PERSONNEL IS HOLDING THE 85 GALLON OVERPACK AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING, FOUR DAMAGED 50 POUNDS BAGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROX. 15 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY, THE BAGS WERE PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING A DUST PAN AND BRUSH.  THE DAMAGED BAGS, REMAINING PRODUCT, FREE PRODUCT AND THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 35 GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE METAL RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER  OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

1)  Was notified by Countest House Truck Stop that we had a spill. App.  3:00 AM 6-26-1999.  2)  When our last driver of the day made his delivery it was raining very heavily!  Approx.  4:30pm 6-25-99. 3)  When notified of spill terminal manager arrived at Countesey House approx. 6:30am 6-26-99 130 miles away from DSI terminal.  4) Contacted clean up crew and started clean up.  5)  Driver was not aware he had a spill -- the heavy rain could have been a factor in him not knowing.

column168: SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT; CAUSE IS YET UNKNOWN.  DRIVER IS DECEASED AND AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT, AUTOPSY REPORT HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETED.  DRIVER RAN OFF THE ROAD AND WAS KILLED.  TANKER OVERTURNED AND RUPTURED, SPILLING THE PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND. LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND HAZMAT RESPONSE CREW RESPONDED.  CREW CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND EXCAVATED CONTAINED SOIL. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS APPROVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT COLUMBIA CO. LANDFILL IN GEORGIA.  CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS TESTED BELOW LIMITS, AND ARRANGEMENTS ARE BEING MADE FOR LANDFILL DISPOSAL.

column168: MISSION DRIVER WAS AT CUSTOMER'S LOCATION.  HE FAILED TO INSURE THAT THE LOADING VALVE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION PRIOR TO ENGAGING THE PRODUCT PUMP ON THE TRAILER.  THIS RESULTED IN A 4128 GALLON SPILL OF TRANSMIX.  THE PRODUCT PUMP WAS NOT SET PROPERLY AND THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT WORKING PROPERLY.  THE DRIVER WAS EXPOSED TO THE SPILL.  HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED BACK TO WORK. THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND CONTAMINATED AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY AFC SERVICES.  THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED BACK INTO STORAGE TANK.  THIS DRIVER WAS TERMINATED DUE TO THIS INCIDENT.
UPON ARRIVAL AT CUSTOMER'S, DISCOVERED TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND DELIVERED TO REPAIR FACILITY TO BE FIXED.

THE DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD HIS WASTE MATERIAL WHEN HE DISCOVERED THAT APPROX 1 QUART OF WASTE HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP OF AN IMPROPERLY SEALED 16 GALLON DRUM.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED YP ANF CONTAINERIZED INTO A FIBER WASTE DRUM.

AN IMPROPERLY SECURED 15 GALLON DRUM TIPPED OVER IN THE BACK OF THE HAULERS TRUCK.   THIS CAUSED THE DRUM LIDS SEAL TO LEAK RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROX 7 GALLON OF LIQUID WASTE.  THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO ANOTHER FIBER DRUM.

column168: DRIVER MADE A DELIVERY TO A NEAR BY SITE AT THIS TIME THE CARTONS SHIFTED AFTER THE DELIVERY WAS MADE.  WHEN THE CARTONS STARTED TO LEAN THE CARTONS LOST ITS STRENGHT. PRODUCT ARRIVES AT OUR DOCK WITH OBVIOUS DAMAGE TO IT.  ONE CORNER OF THE CARTON WAS HEAVILY CRUSHED DOWN ALTHOUGH NO FREIGHT WAS ON TOP OF IT.  DAMAGE OCCURRED IN PRIOR TRANSIT. MOST OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE CARTON AND ABSORBENT PASSING IN THE BOTTOM.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: Tank car was in service for a time-sensitive product.  The ethylene had been in transportation system approx. 26 days when it was examined in Chicago.  Safety valve and rupture disks were covered in approx. 2-3 inches of ice.  The safety valve piping was also iced up outside the valving cabinet.  The relief stack could be heard within 40 ft., with a faint sound of escaping gas.  The shipper recommended the car be moved to consignee as quickly as possible.  Approval was obtained from the FRA to make the emergency move.  The car was delivered approx. 8 hours after discovery.  Better tracking and an awareness and respect from the railroads is necessary to prevent recurrence.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: The tank car of ethylene was in unloading area when another tank car was coupled into it.  At the time of coupling, the car began to vent through its safety relief valve.  This tank car loaded with a time sensitive product had been in transportation system longer than the prescribed time, which is the probable cause of the release. Transportation companies must be more attuned to moving time sensitive materials in a more prompt manner.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: This tank car was involved in a yard derailment earlier in the day. When rerailing was attempted, a hissing sound could be heard in the valve cabinet.  Upon further inspection, a packing nut was loose on one valve, the valve was not completely closed, and a vent cap was loose.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: While loading material at a customer's site, a forklift punctured a five gallon drum of waste paint thinner. Approximately 4.5 gallons of the material spilled. Most of the material was held in secondary containment. Roughly a half gallon of waste spilled over the brim into soil. The contaminated soil was cleaned up and containerized along with the waste material that was absorbed in the secondary containment area. Approximately 40 pounds of additional waste was generated from this spill. This waste, along with the original material, was containerized and taken to the Safety-Kleen facility at 4800 S. Peachtree rd., Norcross, GA 30071, for consolidation and disposal. The driver was counseled regarding loading procedures and reviewed standard forklift training.

While inspecting a load of drums on a truck at a transfer facility, the driver noticed one of the drums leaking. A pinhole leak resulted in less than one gallon of waste spilled onto the floor into secondary containment. The leaking drum was overpacked. The spilled material was absorbed and placed into an approved container for future disposal. This spill generated approximately five pounds of waste that was received at the Safety-Kleen facility for consolidation and transfer to a disposal facility. The drive was counseled to thoroughly check drum integrity prior to loading on to trucks for transportation.

The driver was picking up a drum of waste at the client's site. While changing the defective lid on the drum, the driver spilled approximately one gallon of waste onto his leg and the floor of his truck. The driver absorbed the spill with absorbent pads and containerized the waste for disposal. Subsequently, the driver received first aid for irritation to his leg. This spill generated eight pounds of additional waste that was transported along with the original waste to the Safety Kleen facility at 633 East 138th St., Dolton, IL for reprocessing. The driver was counseled regarding the proper techniques for changing drum lids and transloading waste drums.

AT THE CLIENT'S FACILITY THE DRIVER WAS LOADING A DRUM OF WASTE MATERIAL WHEN THE CONTENTS LEAKED FROM THE LID OF AN IMPROPERLY SEALED 16 GALLON DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF THE LIQUID WASTE SPILLED ONTO THE DRIVER AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO A FIBER WASTE DRUM.  THE LEAKING WAS CORRECTLY RE SEALED.  THE RELEASE PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 6 OF ADDITIONAL WASTE.  THE WASTE WAS SENT ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 2130 EAST GRAUWYLER, IRVING, TX 75061 FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER REVIEWED THE SAFETY-KLEEN STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR MATERIAL PACKAGING AND DRUM HANDLING WITH HIS SUPERVISOR.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO PERFORM BETTER DRUM INSPECTIONS PRIOR TO LOADING MATERIAL.

TRANSFERRING PRODUCT INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  DRIVER OF TRUCK NOTICED HOSE WAS SEEPING PRODUCT.  CONTINUOUS RUBBING ON CONTAINMENT SURFACE RESULTED IN HOSE DEVELOPING A SMALL HOLE, ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT (LESS THAN ONE GALLON) TO SEEP FROM HOSE.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF RELEASE PRODUCT EVAPORATED IMMEDIATELY.  HOSE WAS REPLACED AND HOSE PROTECTION HAS BEEN INSTALLED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WHILE EN ROUTE FROM SPRING VALLEY, MN TO CASHTON, WI THE DRIVER ENTERED A SERIES OF CURVES.  THE LIQUID LOAD SURGED IN THE CARGO TANKER CAUSING THE UNIT TO ROCK TO THE RIGHT AND THEN TO THE LEFT SENDING THE CARGO TANK INTO A ROLL.  THE ROLL WHIPPED THE TRACTOR INTO A ROCK WALL ADJACENT TO THE HIGHWAY.  THE CARGO TANKER IN ROLLING STRUCK A ROCK WHICH PUNCTURED THE TANK SPILLING THE LOAD.  THE DRIVER WAS WELL BELOW THE POSTED LIMIT OF 55 MPH AS LAW ENFORCEMENT ESTIMATED HIS SPEED AS BETWEEN 35 AND 45 MPH. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED DUE TO THE MOVEMENT OF THE CARGO TANK. CLEAN-UP IS IN PROCESS, HOWEVER THEY AS OF THIS DATE HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO LOCATE THE SPILLED DIESEL.  THERE IS A RIVER ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE ROCK AND PRECAUTIONS HAVE BEEN TAKEN IF THE DIESEL SHOULD MAKE ITS WAY TO THE RIVER.  THE RECOVERY CREW HAS DUG 2 FOOT DOWN AND ENCOUNTERED ROCK WITH NO CONTACT OF DIESEL.  IT IS UNKNOWN IF THERE WILL BE ANY ENVIROMENTAL IMPACT FROM THE SPILLED LOAD.

column168: Flight #65 Memphis - Guadalahara, Mexico, had to divert to an unscheduled landing in Houston due to what was believed to be flammable fumes in the aircraft.  Crew went to oxygen and made an uneventful landing in Houston.  Dangerous goods specialist met the aircraft and were quickly met by the fumes.  The aircraft was unloaded to find the leaking packages.  The DG specialist finally found the package causing the problems.  Box contained two chainsaws with gasoline in their fuel tanks.  The gasoline was leaking from the fuel tanks.  The package was not marked, labeled, or documented to contain dangerous goods.  The shipment was held pending FAA investigation.  The local FAA was notified on 6/24.

column168: PHILIPS SERVICES ARRANGED FOR THE TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL OF WASTEWATER (WATER WITH LUBEOIL) FORM COPELAND DE MEXICO (IN REYNOSA, MEXICO).  THE SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP BY AN ALUMINUM TRAILER OWNED BY TRANSPORTES GOR AT THE COPELAND FACILITY IN THE MORNING ON JUNE 28, 1999 TO BE DELIVERED TO EMPACK ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL TRANSPORTES GOR PARKED THE TRAILER ON INTERTRANSPORT YARD IN PHARR, TEXAS AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30PM, AFTER CLEARING U.S. CUSTOMS.  THE TRAILER STARTED REACTING TO THE PRODUCT AT ABOUT 4:30 PM, SO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED.  TRANSPORTES GOR REMOVED THE POWER UNIT AND PLACED THE TANKER ON RAILROAD TIES.  AT 5:00 PM, THE TANKER COLLAPSED AND RELEASED THE CONTENTS ONTO A DIRT GRAVE LOT. NADINE HILL, TNRCC REPRESENTATIVE, ARRIVED ONSITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS AND OBSERVED THE SITE AND INITIAL CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  IT WAS AGREED THAT CLEAN-UP WOULD BE SUCCESSFUL ONCE SOIL SAMPLES INDICATED A PH OF APPROXIMATELY PH 8.  PHILIP SERVICES ASSISTED IN CONTACTING A CONTRACTOR (ALAMO ENVIRONMENTAL) TO REMOVE THE POTENTIALLY CONTAMINATED SOIL AND MAKE NOTIFICATIONS TO THE TNRCC FOR THE RELEASE.  ALAMO ENVIRONMENTAL REMOVED 2 INCHES OF SOIL AND CHECK  THE PH TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN-UP.  PHILIP SERVICES ASSISTED WITH THE DISPOSAL OF 44 DRUMS OF LIQUID AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL TO THE PROPER FACILITIES.

DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAK DURING CARGO INSPECTION.  TRAILER FLOOR WAS SEALED SO LEAKING MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE TRAILER.  DRIVER TIGHTENED RINGS AND CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL WITH FLOOR DRY.  ALL MATERIALS TAKEN TO TSDF IN KENT.  NO MATERIAL LEFT TRAILER.

UPON CHECKING THE LOAD, SUBSTANCE WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER ADVISED TO PUT OIL DRY ON FLOOR TO ABSORB LIQUID, THEN PROCEED BACK TO THE LOADING POINT.  TRAILER WAS OFF LOADED, CLEANED, DRUM  WAS REPLACED.  PALLET WAS SHRINK WRAPPED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: JACK B KELLY, INC WAS TRANSPORTING A LIQUID HYDROGEN TRAILER BELONGING TO PRAXAIR. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER OVERTURNED ON SR-91 (WEST BOUND) IN CORONA, CALIFORNIA. THE ACCIDENT OCCURED AT APPROXIMATELY 16:35 ON 6/18/99. A RED TOYOTA CAME ACROSS THE HIGHWAY AND STARTED TO SPIN JUST AS IT GOT TO THE TRUCK AND ENDED UP FACING THE TRUCK HEAD ON. THE DRIVER TRIED TO MAKE AN EVASIVE MOVE TO THE RIGHT LANE, WHILE ALSO APPLYING THE BRAKES VERY HARD, BUT WAS STRUCK IN THE LEFT FRONT OF HIS TRACTOR. THE IMPACT RIPPED THE LEFT FRONT SPRING HANGER OFF THE FRAME, SHIFTING THE AXLE TO THE REAR OF THE TRACTOR, WHICH CAUSED THE STEERING WHEEL TO TURN SHARP TO THE LEFT. THIS CAUSED THE TRACTOR STEERING WHEEL TO SPIN IN THE DRIVER'S HANDS. AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER HAD NO CONTROL OVER THE STEERING OF THE TRACTOR, THE CAR CONTINUED TO SPIN AND THEN HIT THE FRONT DRIVER AXLE ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE. THE VEHICLES CAME TO REST ABOUT 40 FEET APART. THE DRIVER AND HIS PASSENGER IN THE TRUCK STATED THAT THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE NEARLY STOPPED WHEN THE LIQUID IN THE TANK TRAILER SHIFTED CAUSING THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT TO ROLLOVER ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. NO INJURIES TO THE DRIVER AND HIS PASSENGER, THE DRIVER OF THE AUTOMOBILE AND HER PASSENGER HAD MINOR INJURIES BUT DID NOT GO TO THE HOSPITAL. column168: PETE SAWICKI WAS ENROUTE TO PVS TECHNOLOGIES IN DETROIT ON M-60, STOPPED AT A ROAD CONSTRUCTION SITE WHEN THE TWO LANE ROAD NARROWED TO ONE LANE. HE WAS STOPPED FOR 3-5 MINUTES WITH FOOT ON BRAKE PEDAL AND 4 WAY FLASHERS GOING. THERE WERE 3-4 CARS STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM AND A ROAD CONSTRUCTION WORKER WITH A STOP SIGN HALTING EASTBOUND TRAFFIC. PETE WAS DRINKING COFFEE, WAITING FOR HIS LANE TO START MOVING, WHEN HE FELT A BANG AND  THE TRUCK JERK FORWARD. THE COFFEE CUP FLEW OUT OF HIS HANDS AND HE LOOKED AT THE CAR IN FRONT OF HIM. HIS TRUCK BUMPED THE CAR IN FRONT OF HIM (NO DAMAGE TO THE CAR). PETE LOOKED IN THE MIRROR AND ALL HE SAW WAS SMOKE/STEAM. HE COULDN'T TELL WHAT HIT HIM. HE SHUT OFF THE MOTOR AND PUT THE TRACTOR/TRAILER BRAKES ON AND JUMPED OUT OF THE TRUCK. PETE RAN TOWARDS THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND SAW IT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE UNLOADING VALVE, THEN RAN TO THE TRUCK THAT REAR-ENDED HIM. STEAM FROM THE RADIATOR ENGULFED THE TRACTOR; HE TRIED TO OPEN THE DRIVER DOOR BUT IT WAS JAMMED SHUT. THE DRIVER, FROM JET EXPRESS, HAD HIS WINDOW DOWN AND SAID HIS KNEE AND HEAD HURT AND HE DIDN'T REALIZE THAT PETE HAD STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM. PETE ASKED IF ANYONE HAD CALLED FOR HELP AND WAS TOLD BY A MAN ON THE SCENE THAT THE CONSTRUCTION CREW HAD WALKIE TALKIE AND HAD CALLED FOR HELP. PETE WENT TO HIS TRUCK TO CALL PVS BUT HIS TRACTOR PHONE WAS DEAD. HE USED HIS PERSONAL CELLULAR AND NOTIFIED BOB PEPIN AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 P.M. THAT HE HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN AND ACCIDENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FROM THE VILLAGE OF HOMER ARRIVED-- ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF KURT SWOPE. PETE TOLD THEM WHAT WAS LEAKING (FERROUS CHLORIDE) AND TOLD THEM THAT SAND WAS NEEDED TO DIKE AROUND THE SPILL. PETE TALKED TO THE CALHOUN COUNTY SHERIFF, TOOK PICTURES OF THE SCENE, CALLED BOB PEPIN AT APPROXIMATELY 12:50 P.M. WITH AN UPDATE. WHEN SAND ARRIVED FROM THE COUNTY, PETE TALKED WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ABOUT DIKING. DOT ARRIVED AND TOOK PETE'S REPORT AND CHECKED HIS LOG AND PAPERWORK. PETER THEN TALKED TO AL ISENEGGER AT PVS WHO WAS LEAVING FOR THE SCENE, ALONG WITH CARL SCHRADE AND ANOTHER VAC TRAILER ( TRACTOR 40-TRAILER 26V). WHEN CARL AND AL ARRIVED, PETE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DISCUSSED THE CLEAN UP PLAN WITH THEM. PVS PERSONNEL SUITED UP AND STARTED CLEANUP WITHIN 15 MINUTES OF ARRIVAL. PETE OPENED THE DOME TOP AFTER THE VAC WAS ALREADY RUNNING TO MINIMIZE THE SPILL. THE TRACTOR WAS VAC'D OUT FIRST, THEN THE SPILL ON THE GROUND. 3650  GALLONS WAS VAC'D INTO 26V, AND MANIFESTED FOR TRANSPORT TO DYNECLO FOR DISPOSAL. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 P.M., WHEN THE JET EXPRESS TRACTOR HAD BEEN DETACHED FROM THE PVS TRACTOR/TRAILER, CARL LEFT THE PETE FOR DYNECOL. ESTIMATED SPILL WAS 297 GALLONS, CONTAINED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. THE HOMER FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP. YOUNG'S WAS ON SITE FROM 6:30 P.M. UNTIL MIDNIGHT. TWO 20 YARD BOXES WERE USED TO REMOVE 40 YARDS OF DIRT AND SAND FROM THE ROAD SHOULDER. APPROXIMATELY 25 YARDS OF SAN

column168: THIS SPILL WAS DUE TO IMPROPER SECURING OF THE LOADED CONTAINER TO THE SEMI TRAILER TRANSPORTING IT.  A STEEL EDGING WAS IN PLACE TO KEEP CONTAINER ON FLAT BED, BUT CONTAINER WAS SUCKED OFF TRAILER WHEN IT MET ANOTHER SEMI TRUCK ON A 2 LANE HIGHWAY.  CONTAINER WAS LESS THAN 1/2 FULL THEREFORE THE WIND AND SUCTION ALLOWED CONTAINER TO TIP OVER SIDE OF TRAILER.  IN THE FUTURE ALL CONTAINERS ARE TRIPLE SECURED WITH PROPER HEAVY DUTY LOAD BINDERS AND STRAPS.  SOME BEING CHAIN WITH BINDERS OR STRAPS WITH RACKETS TIE DOWNS.  THE INCIDENT CAUSED NO INJURIES.  NO PROPERTY DAMAGE WAS DONE TO TRUCK OR TRAILER.  CONTAINER WAS DESTROYED BEYOND REPAIR.  THE CHEMICAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.  ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS SPREAD ON ROADWAY TO ABSORB MATERIAL, THEN SWEPT UP.  ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND RUPTURED CONTAINER WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  AN INSPECTOR INSPECTED THE SITE AND DECLARED IF A PROPERLY CLEANED UP SPILL.

SEVERAL ITEMS IN THE BOX OF THE TRUCK WERE KNOCKED LOOSE AND SOMETHING HIT A FITTING ON THE CARGO TANK. THE PERRY TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE VANDERBURGH SHERIFF'S OFFICE SECURED THE SCENE UNTIL THE OXYGEN HAD COMPLETED VENTING.  BOTH VEHICLES WERE TOWED FROM THE SCENE. A passenger checked a box of undeclared materials that contained approximately 9 boxes of cleaning products.  The box originated on SWAA flight 901 in Houston, Texas (OHU)  and transferred to flight 487 in St. Louis, MO (STL).  The shipment was discovered in Detroit (DTW) by Southwest personnel.  The box contained a wide variety of cleaning products in various sizes and types.  Included were aerosols, a cigarette lighter, and various liquid cleaners (bleach, lime away).  The box was discovered due to the apparent leak of one of the products.  The FAA (DTW CASFO) was notified of the potential incident and performed an investigation.  The leak itself (specific chemical) was not ascertainable from the investigation.  Due to the fact that we could not determine which chemical had leaked, section 12 of the 5800.1 was left blank and the packaging information/failure is somewhat vague.

column168: A passenger checked a bag with undeclared hazardous material in El Paso, TX.  The bag contained a single plastic bottle (approx. 8 ounces) of Ether that was wrapped in plastic bags and placed in a "Tupperware" container.  A DAL Ramp Agent discovered the material during the off loading of the flight.  Upon opening the bin of the aircraft, the Ramp Agent noticed the odor of Ether but could not identify a leaking bag or spill.  He called over a mechanic to verify the smell and then began checking baggage for the source.  It was determined that the lid of the "Tupperware" had come off in flight and the material was leaking.  The Ramp Agent notified his supervisor and was instructed to call the Dallas Police Dept. and Corporate Safety.  The DAL Station held the material and the FAA was notified the next morning.  The customer who transported the material was an elderly Hispanic lady that said it is a custom to rub ether on the belly of a mother just after she has given birth to speed the healing process.  She was coming to Dallas for the birth of a grandbaby.

column168: AB4199D, Shipper: Conquest Div., Gulfstream.  AWB# SBN 4421072132 SAN.  This is an undeclared hazardous materials shipment.  There were no markings, labels or shipper's declaration for dangerous goods attached to or accompanying this shipment to indicate the contents were a regulated material.  On 06/28/99, at 02:02 a spill was reported in A building of our sort facility.  Part time hazardous materials spill technicians Matthew Grosvenor and Alan Henderson donned personal protective clothing and responded to the spill.  Upon arrival they found a brown fiberboard box emitting a white powder.  They opened the box and found 1 10 llb BC fire extinguisher packed in white foam.  The fire extinguisher had discharged during transit, releasing all of the fire extinguishing powder.  The pin that secures the fire extinguisher handle was broken causing the fire extinguisher handle to deploy releasing the extinguishing powder.  They swept up the powder and placed it into a plastic bag.  They placed the bag inside the box, resealed the box and placed it into a recovery drum.

column168: RENN DRIVER CLIFFORD HOUSE WAS WB ON SR 20 FOR DELIVERY OF CRD TO MENDOCINO COAST PETROLEUM.  AT 09:30 C. HOUSE WAS  INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT IN TRUCK 380 TRAILER 81 & 82.  THE SCENE OF THE COLLISION MILEPOST 26.53 ON SR 20 IS EB/WB MOUNTAIN ROADWAY CONSISTING OF TWO LANES.  THE ROADWAY IS CURVED LEFT & HAS A NEGATIVE GRADE WHEN TRAVELING WEST.  SURFACE IS PRIMARILY OF ASPHALT.  LOAD WAS CARB. RED DIESEL #2 IN BOTH TRAILERS, PLACARDED UN1993 IN ACCORDANCE WITH DOT REGULATIONS.  CLIFFORD HOUSE STATED THE HE WAS DRIVING WB ON SR 20 ENTERED A CURVE ABOUT 20 MPH POSTED SPEED LIMIT AS HE WAS ABOUT HALFWAY THROUGH THE CURVE CLIFF SAID HE HEARD A GROWL AND THE RIGHT FRONT OF THE TRUCK TIPPED DOWN.  CLIFF THOUGHT HE HAD BLOWN THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE.  CONTINUED AROUND THE CURVE TRYING TO KEEP TRUCK FROM HITTING THE GUARDRAIL.  CLIFF WAS UNABLE TO AVOID HITTING THE RAIL, TRUCK AND FIRST TRAILER OVERTURNED.  THERE WAS 1 WITNESS, DAVID MICHEAL MORA.  MR MORA RELATED HE HAD BEEN FOLLOWING THE TRUCK FOR APPROX 4 MILES W OF WILLIS, CA.  MR MORA SAID THEY WERE BOTH DRIVING ABOUT 20 MPH AND HAD BEEN DOING THAT SPEED SINCE HE HAD CAUGHT THE TRUCK.  MR MORA SAID THE TRUCK ENTERED THE CURVE AND DROVE TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  WHEN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK HIT THE GUARDRAIL IT WENT OVER.  POSSIBLE CAUSE, THE LOAD SHIFTED TO THE FRONT AND THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE FIRST TANK TRAILER WITH THE ROAD HAVING A NEGATIVE GRADE THE WEIGHT OF THE PRODUCT A 10% DOWNGRADE AND SHARP CURVE CAUSE THE TRUCK TO HIT THE GUARD RAIL WHICH THEN CAUSED THE TRUCK AND 1ST TRAILER TO OVERTURN.  GUARDRAIL RIPPED PART OF THE OVERTURN OR VAPOR RAIL OPEN AND THE VAPOR INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TANK, WHICH CAUSED THE SPILL.  DAMAGE TO 2ND TRAILER CONSISTED OF REPLACING THE WIRING HARNESS AND DRAW BAR EYE THAT CONNECTS TO THE 1ST TRAILER.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVEREDA DAMAGED CONTAINER.  THE AREA WASISOLATED AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.  AN MSDS HAD TRAVELLED WITH SHIPMENT.  ABOSORBENT WAS USED TO CONTAIN FREE PRODUCT.  AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WAS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.  REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT WAS UNDAMAGED AND IS BEING FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: DRIVER HAD PICKED UP A TRAILER THAT WAS LOADED, UPON HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION HE DID NOT NOTICE THAT THE WASH OUT CAP WAS NOT TIGHTENED PROPERLY.  AS HE PROCEEDED TO GO TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY A PASSING MOTORIST CALLED HIM ON HIS CB RADIO TO INFORM HIM THAT SOME PRODUCT HAD GOTTEN ONTO HIS AUTOMOBILE.  AFTER STOPPING HE ADVISED THE DRIVER TO GO WASH HIS AUTOMOBILE OFF AS QUICKLY AS HE COULD.  THE DRIVER (JACK SAMMONS) CALLED FAIRBURN TERMINAL AND THEN THEY CAME OUT AND THE PRODUCT HAD NO NOTICEABLE APPEARANCE OF A SPILL ONTO THE HIGHWAY.  THEY BROUGHT HIM A WASH OUT CAP AND AFTER INSTALLING IT HE WENT ON TO OFF LOAD.

column168: ON 6-23-99, TANK CAR UTLX 47579 WAS SIDESWIPPED AND DERAILED.  DUE TO THE DERAILMENT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SHEARED OFF.   CAR WAS RERAILED AND PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED.

UPPER FORT WORTH COMMAND CENTER REPORTED THAT TANK CAR APHX2002, ENTRAIN ON THE MEPFW 20, WAS VENTING.  THE VAPOR CLOUD WAS OBSERVED AND REPORTED BY A PASSING TRAIN.  UPRR CTS MGR. ARLA ROQUET CARTER AND UPRR CAR FOREMAN GENERAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND A VAPOR CLOUD SURROUNDING APHX2002 THAT WAS APPROXIMATELY 4 FOOT HIGH, 40-60 FOOT LONG AND 10 FOOT WIDE.  THERE WAS NO WIND, HIGH HUMIDITY AND THE VAPOR WAS HOLDING THE GROUND.  RMCC WAS REQUESTED TO NOTIFIED CORRIDOR MANAGER TO STOP ALL TRAIN TRAFFIC AND TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER, CONTRACTED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND.  SHIPPERS RESPONDERS FROM ODESSA AND HOUSTON WERE EN ROUTE.  INSPECTION FOUND THAT A FITTING HAD CAME OFF OF A QUARTER INCH LINE AND WAS THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE.  THE FITTING WAS RE-APPLIED AND THE RELEASE STOPPED.  THE TRACK WAS OKAYED FOR TRAIN MOVEMENT AT 0803 HOURS., 6-23-99, BUT THE MEPFW 20 WAS HELD PENDING INSPECTION BY SHIPPER.  THE CAR AND TRAIN WERE RELEASED AS GOOD TO GO AT 1153 HOURS.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE RAMP MANAGER, ICTF STATING AN OUTSIDE DRAYMAN REPORTED A LEAKING IM TANK. MANAGER COOPER MET THE DRAYMAN AT THE SOUTH CRANE PAD, WHERE THE CONTAINERS ARE FLIPPED TO THE CUSTOMERS CHASSIS. THE DRIVE STATED HE HAD INSPECTED THE TOP MANWAY OF THE IM TANK AND NOTED SOME PRODUCT TRAILS IN THE SPILL BOX. HE STATED THE MARINE TERMINAL WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE IM TANK IF IT SHOWED ANY SIGNS OF PRODUCT SPILLAGE. THE PRODUCT TRAILS WERE DRY, AND IT WAS EVIDENT THE PRODUCT HAD COME FROM THE MANWAY. ALL OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHT, WHICH LEAD TO THE GASKET BEING THE CULPRIT. INSPECTION OF THE GASKET SHOWED NO SIGNS OF BEING DEFORMED OR TORN. CONTACT WITH HOYER TANK LINES IN TEXAS, DEVELOPED SEVERAL TANKS HAD BEEN LOADED AT THE DEGUSSA FACILITY IN THEODORE, ALABAMA, AND THERE WAS NO DOCUMENTATION ON THE MANWAY GASKET BEING REPLACED PRIOR TO LOADING. HOYER TANK LINES CONTACTED FOSS ENVIORMENTAL AND HAD THEM RESPOND TO REPLACE THE MANNWAY GASKET AND CLEANED THE DRIED RESIDUE FROM THE SPILL BOX. WHILE THIS EFFORT WAS UNDERWAY, HOYER IDENTIFIED THE FOLLOWING IM TANKS AND REQUESTED THEY BE INSPECTED AND HAVE THE MANWAY  GASKETS REPLACED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.ALL WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE MANWAY GASKETS WERE REPLACED DURING THE INSPECTION PROCESS. ONCE THE TANK WERE INSPECTED, THEY WERE RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE HARBOR FOR VESSEL LOADING. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY,WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR. THE CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR BY THE WEST END SWITCH CREW AND IT WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YEMO YARD, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE SAFETY VENT.THE SAFETY VENT IA A STANDARD GATX TRIVENT MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THE VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED,THE BURST FRANGIBLE DISC REMOVED, AND REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 165 POUND DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED. IT APPEARS THE CAR WAS SUBJECTED TO AN OVERSPEED IMPACT FROM SWITCHING,  WHICH CAUSED A LIQUID SURGE AGAINST THE SAFETY VENT. DUE TO MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR INFORMATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN YEMO, CALIFORNIA. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS,YEMO, WHO STATED THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT WAS INSPECTING AN OUTBOUND TRAIN (WESTBOUND) AND OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE TANK CAR. AS THE CAR WAS ALREADY PLACED IN THE TRAIN, IT WAS PLACED AND THE TRAIN CALL TIME WAS CANCELED. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YEMO YARD, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND PRODUCT BEING DISCHARGED FROM THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MILAND STYLE VENT WITH COVER, WAS MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. INSPECTION OF THE VENT FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD BURST, AND THE PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE EXPANDING FROM EXPOSURE TO THE HEAT. THE LIQUID WAS DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR, AND ONTO THE TRACK BED BELOW. AN AREA ROUGHLY 4 FEET LONG UNDER THE CAR HAD VISIBLE PRODUCT STAINS. APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR AFTER INSPECTING THE CAR, THE PRODUCT STOPPED DRIPPING FROM THE SAFETY VENT. THE VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED, THE BURST DISC WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS& B STAINLESS/ TEFLON 160 POUND DISC. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THE LOAD WOULD REQUIRE REDUCING TO PREVENT A SIMILAR EVENT. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION

DEAN C COOPER MANGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. MANAGER COOPER LOCATED THE CONTAINER IN YELLOW ROW, SPACE#256, AND OBSERVED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID ON THE GROUND AT THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER  WAS DIAPERED TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LOSS OF PRODUCT, AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION. ONCE THE REAR DOORS WERE OPENED, DEVELOPED THE LADING CONSISTED OF METAL 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT, AND SECURED WITH TY-GARD MATERIAL. THE ENTIRE INTERIOR OF THE CONTAINER WAS COVERED WITH PRODUCT, WHICH HAD DRIED.IT APPEARS THE PRODUCT REACTED IN ONE OF THE TOP STACK DRUMS, WHICH CAUSED THE DRUM TO LAUNCH. THE DRUM IMPACTED THE ROOF OF THE CONTAINER AND SETTLED BACK INTO THE LOAD. AS THE PRODUCT HAD DRIED, IT APPEARS THIS EVENT OCCURRED WHILE IN TRANSIT. CONTACT WITH SOLAR INTL SHIPPING FAILED ACCOUNT THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE BILL WAS A DISCONNECTED NUMBER. CONTACT WITH BAYER, THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT  WAS MADE THROUGH CHEMTREC. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH TEC TO OFF LOAD THE DRUMS AND FIND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT. THE DRUM THAT REACTED WAS ON THE TOP STACK, 3 ROWS FROM THE NOSE EOF THE CONTAINER. THE TOP AND BOTTOM HEADS HAD BEEN BLOWN OUT OF THE DRUM, AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE LOST WITHIN THE CONTAINER. IT APPEARS THAT APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THIS DRUM. ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE DECONED AS THEY WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE ONE DAMAGE DRUM WAS PATCHED, AND PLACED INTO AND OVERPACK DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. IT WAS ALSO PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER WITH THE ORIGINAL LOAD. ONCE THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

DEAN C COOPER MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING BY THE WEST END SWITCH CREW WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  ALL OF THE FITTINGS AND CLOSURES WERE FOUND TO BE INTACT.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AROUND IT INDICATING THE CAR HAD VENTED.  INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE FOUND THE VALVE TO BE SECURE AND APPEARED TO BE FUNCTIONAL.  IT APPEARS THE CAR WAS SUBJECTED TO AN OVER SPEED SWITCH, WHICH CAUSED THE LIQUID IN THE CAR TO SURGE OUT THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

MANAGER WILDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM RMCC THAT A INTER MODAL TANK CAR WAS LEAKING AT THE GATE AT DOLTON, IL. NO WATER WAYS OR DRAINS INVOLVED.
